# research Journal 1

## May 13, 2026 (Day 3 of Summer Research)

### Overview
The first three days of summer research have been devoted to setting up the 
laboratory under the guidance of Prof. Yan Liu, in preparation for the 
installation of the dark matter detection refrigerator next week.

### Lab Setup
These past three days were physically demanding but deeply rewarding. Under 
Prof. Liu's direction, we assembled furniture and organized the lab space with 
remarkable precision. Every component and its placement was carefully considered 
for its potential long-term impact on our experiments. We wiped down all 
electronic instruments, aligned the benches properly, and ensured that sensitive 
equipment was positioned away from power sources and potential interference.

This experience gave me a first-hand appreciation of the rigorous and meticulous 
mindset required in experimental physics research.

### Technical Skills
This morning, Prof. Liu guided me through installing Claude on the terminal and 
introduced me to the UMN MSI (Minnesota Supercomputing Institute) system. I also 
began self-studying Git as preparation for the formal research work ahead.

### Group Meetings
Over the past two days, I attended my first group meetings and observed how real 
research is conducted collaboratively. Each member takes turns presenting updates, 
offering suggestions, and discussing solutions — all under the leadership of the 
PI. Every step requires both rigor and teamwork. I feel truly honored to be part 
of this process.

### Reflection
Though tired, I feel fulfilled. These three days have shown me what genuine 
scientific research looks like — not just the technical work, but the culture, 
the discipline, and the collaboration that make it all possible.
